1
00:00:04,671 --> 00:00:07,674
[CLUB MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

2
00:00:11,845 --> 00:00:14,765
Whatever you're listening to,
it ain't music.

3
00:00:15,516 --> 00:00:16,767
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

4
00:00:16,934 --> 00:00:20,562
-There ought to be a law.
-Well, there's not. So...

5
00:00:20,729 --> 00:00:23,315
[CLUB MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

6
00:00:23,899 --> 00:00:24,942
[GUN CLICKS]

7
00:00:30,739 --> 00:00:32,741
GUARD:
Yo, watch it.

8
00:00:39,998 --> 00:00:41,458
Hey, he's got a gun.

9
00:00:43,252 --> 00:00:45,337
[MEN GROANING]

10
00:00:47,923 --> 00:00:49,424
[BOTH COUGHING]

11
00:00:55,973 --> 00:00:57,182
[GUNFIRE]

12
00:01:17,286 --> 00:01:18,912
THEA:
Tahitian Green or Midnight Black?

13
00:01:19,079 --> 00:01:21,790
-What do you think?
-You've been dropping hints all week.

14
00:01:21,957 --> 00:01:23,834
Mom still isn't buying you a car.

15
00:01:24,001 --> 00:01:27,796
-I could not have said it better myself.
-Oliver got a car when he turned 18.

16
00:01:27,963 --> 00:01:31,300
Yeah, but I could back it out
of the driveway without hitting a tree.

17
00:01:31,466 --> 00:01:34,303
I do remember you taking the paint off
your dad's Maserati.

18
00:01:34,469 --> 00:01:36,722
-Hmm.
MOIRA: Thea, the party planner's waiting.

19
00:01:36,888 --> 00:01:38,640
Sorry to run off like this.

20
00:01:38,807 --> 00:01:40,767
But we have a convertible to go buy.

21
00:01:40,934 --> 00:01:43,228
OLIVER: Good luck.
MOIRA: Yes.

22
00:01:43,395 --> 00:01:47,149
-How's she holding up?
-Oh, she's okay.

23
00:01:47,316 --> 00:01:49,693
Thea thinks she's actually
a little bit too okay.

24
00:01:49,860 --> 00:01:51,612
-What do you mean?
-Just...

25
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:55,198
...behaving erratically. Shut-in one minute,
running the company the next.

26
00:01:55,365 --> 00:01:58,535
Her husband is missing
and presumed who-knows-what.

27
00:01:58,702 --> 00:02:01,538
If anyone had an excuse to be erratic,
it's your mom.

28
00:02:01,705 --> 00:02:03,999
That's what I told Thea.

29
00:02:04,166 --> 00:02:08,879
<i>Department's got the same comment about
this heist as the other two. No comment.</i>

30
00:02:09,421 --> 00:02:11,590
<i>S.C.P.D. may not be willing
to go on record...</i>

31
00:02:11,757 --> 00:02:14,885
<i>...but traffic cameras got the entire heist
in this exclusive.</i>

32
00:02:15,052 --> 00:02:17,179
MAN: <i>Shortly after 1 a.m.,
three masked robbers...</i>

33
00:02:17,346 --> 00:02:20,641
<i>...approached the armored vehicle
after launching what appears...</i>

34
00:02:20,807 --> 00:02:23,352
TOMMY: That's why you keep
all your money offshore.

35
00:02:23,518 --> 00:02:25,812
MAN [ON TV]: <i>One guard was
pronounced dead on the scene.</i>

36
00:02:25,979 --> 00:02:28,190
<i>The other died en route
to Starling General.</i>

37
00:02:28,357 --> 00:02:30,567
<i>Their identities have not yet
been released.</i>

38
00:02:33,403 --> 00:02:36,239
DIGGLE: With all the guys up top,
you might want a side entrance...

39
00:02:36,406 --> 00:02:40,410
-...for your, uh, Arrowcave.
OLIVER: Unh!

40
00:02:40,577 --> 00:02:45,332
Just put one in. South alleyway.
Ah. There's something I wanna show you.

41
00:02:45,916 --> 00:02:48,919
You're into online dating
and you need help with your profile.

42
00:02:49,086 --> 00:02:52,506
Not exactly.
But there's somebody I'd like to meet.

43
00:02:53,340 --> 00:02:56,760
Yeah, I read about this.
Third truck to get hit this month.

44
00:02:56,927 --> 00:02:58,970
I saw it on the news this morning.

45
00:02:59,137 --> 00:03:01,807
Couldn't figure out
why it seemed so familiar.

46
00:03:01,973 --> 00:03:04,685
Then I remembered this. Kandahar, '09.

47
00:03:04,851 --> 00:03:07,270
The Marines took out
a Taliban transport vehicle.

48
00:03:07,437 --> 00:03:09,188
DIGGLE:
Yeah. Well, there's a reason...

49
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:13,402
...why that looks similar. These guys run
the same technique. Where'd you find this?

50
00:03:13,568 --> 00:03:16,863
Researching someone.
Bodyguard who works for a security firm.

51
00:03:17,030 --> 00:03:21,243
Blackhawk Squad Protection Group.
His name is Ted Gaynor.

52
00:03:21,410 --> 00:03:25,204
Oliver, Ted Gaynor was my commanding
officer my first tour in Afghanistan.

53
00:03:28,750 --> 00:03:32,170
Dig, I'm sorry...

54
00:03:34,923 --> 00:03:37,342
...but Gaynor's on the list.

55
00:03:37,509 --> 00:03:39,761
Gaynor's a few
hundred thousand dollars short.

56
00:03:39,928 --> 00:03:42,305
I never said it was just
1 percenters, did I?

57
00:03:42,472 --> 00:03:47,102
This guy saved my life.
Received a commendation for it.

58
00:03:47,269 --> 00:03:49,938
Don't care what your book says,
he's not a stick-up man.

59
00:03:50,105 --> 00:03:53,150
-You haven't known him a long time.
-We both kept in contact...

60
00:03:53,316 --> 00:03:54,568
...since we got stateside.

61
00:03:54,735 --> 00:03:57,487
Six months ago,
he even offered me a job at Blackhawk.

62
00:03:57,654 --> 00:03:59,781
Trust me, you don't know this man
like I do.

63
00:03:59,948 --> 00:04:04,119
I know in Afghanistan his training specialty
was M32 multiple grenade launchers.

64
00:04:04,286 --> 00:04:06,371
The exact same weapon used
in these heists.

65
00:04:06,538 --> 00:04:09,750
Not exactly something you find
at your local sporting goods store.

66
00:04:09,916 --> 00:04:13,086
Two months ago we found out
this wasn't even your father's book.

67
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:16,882
Written by whoever hired the other archer.
Doesn't that beg the question...

68
00:04:17,048 --> 00:04:21,470
-...what else you could be wrong about?
-I can be wrong. The list isn't.

69
00:04:21,636 --> 00:04:25,640
Now, I'm gonna have a pointed
conversation with Mr. Gaynor tonight.

70
00:04:25,807 --> 00:04:27,350
We'll see what he has to say.

71
00:04:29,478 --> 00:04:32,481
I understand
if you wanna take the week off.

72
00:04:32,647 --> 00:04:34,399
Yeah, well, thank you.

73
00:04:36,067 --> 00:04:37,235
Sir.

74
00:05:07,390 --> 00:05:08,475
[MEN CHATTERING]

75
00:05:35,377 --> 00:05:37,379
[SOLIDER SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

76
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,800
SOLDIER:
Different day, same slop.

77
00:05:42,384 --> 00:05:44,469
-You new?
OLIVER: Yeah.

78
00:05:44,636 --> 00:05:45,679
[SOLDIER CHUCKLES]

79
00:05:45,846 --> 00:05:49,224
SOLDIER: Don't worry. Took me a year
to find my way around the island.

80
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:51,142
OLIVER:
Well, hey, hey, hey.

81
00:05:53,436 --> 00:05:56,565
I'm supposed to be transporting
a prisoner.

82
00:05:56,731 --> 00:05:58,817
Chinese guy who wears a green hood?

83
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:01,319
SOLDIER: Sounds like the guy
they took to east camp.

84
00:06:01,486 --> 00:06:03,822
I'm heading over that way.
You can hitch a ride.

85
00:06:04,614 --> 00:06:06,449
Let's go, come on.

86
00:06:16,585 --> 00:06:20,672
Hold up, hold up. Unit one, two.

87
00:06:24,426 --> 00:06:26,136
[FYERS GROANING]

88
00:06:35,937 --> 00:06:38,982
That wall over there
still has to be taped and textured.

89
00:06:39,149 --> 00:06:43,111
I need you to grout the hallway floor as
soon as they're done with the tile install.

90
00:06:43,278 --> 00:06:44,946
[PHONE BEEPING]

91
00:06:45,113 --> 00:06:46,197
MAN:
All right.

92
00:06:47,490 --> 00:06:49,451
-Yeah.
-Hey, Tommy.

93
00:06:49,618 --> 00:06:52,621
-Dad, I am really busy.
-<i>Tommy, I know things have been...</i>

94
00:06:52,787 --> 00:06:54,664
...well, strained between us since...

95
00:06:54,831 --> 00:06:57,334
Since you cut me off
and told me that I was a loser?

96
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:00,128
I was just trying
to jolt you into adulthood.

97
00:07:00,295 --> 00:07:03,048
<i>And look at you now.
You've got your first job, heh.</i>

98
00:07:03,214 --> 00:07:05,383
My tough love worked.

99
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:07,052
What do you want, Dad?

100
00:07:08,011 --> 00:07:11,181
Nothing more than to share a meal
with my son.

101
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:12,474
Dinner, tomorrow night?

102
00:07:12,641 --> 00:07:14,851
-Laurel and I have plans.
MALCOLM: <i>Bring her along.</i>

103
00:07:15,018 --> 00:07:18,939
I think it's time I got to know her
a little better. Tommy...

104
00:07:20,357 --> 00:07:23,860
...I've said some pretty hurtful things
and I regret them.

105
00:07:24,861 --> 00:07:26,237
But you're still my son...

106
00:07:26,404 --> 00:07:29,532
<i>...and I still want
what I've always wanted.</i>

107
00:07:31,451 --> 00:07:33,328
For us to be close.

108
00:07:35,413 --> 00:07:38,166
Let me check with Laurel
and I'll get back to you.

109
00:07:49,970 --> 00:07:51,513
[DART GUN FIRING]

110
00:08:11,783 --> 00:08:13,326
[GRUNTS]

111
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:15,829
Ted, we're gonna have a conversation.

112
00:08:15,996 --> 00:08:20,542
You make a move, go for a gun,
anything and things will end badly for you.

113
00:08:20,709 --> 00:08:21,710
[GUN COCKS]

114
00:08:21,876 --> 00:08:23,920
Put the bow down.

115
00:08:40,603 --> 00:08:42,313
[SIGHS]

116
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:53,241
[SIGHS]

117
00:08:53,408 --> 00:08:55,618
It's all clear. You okay?

118
00:08:55,785 --> 00:08:58,580
Uh, yeah.

119
00:08:59,414 --> 00:09:03,960
Well, I gotta talk to my boss
but after what I just saw...

120
00:09:04,127 --> 00:09:06,546
...I'd say you're as good as hired.

121
00:09:06,713 --> 00:09:08,965
Hell of a job interview, Ted.

122
00:09:09,132 --> 00:09:11,843
Usually the vigilante
only goes after rich schmucks.

123
00:09:12,010 --> 00:09:14,888
Any reason why he would change
his MO for you?

124
00:09:16,598 --> 00:09:17,640
[SIGHS]

125
00:09:17,807 --> 00:09:22,687
You've known me a long time, John.
What do you think?

126
00:09:25,273 --> 00:09:26,608
[SIGHS]

127
00:09:26,775 --> 00:09:28,943
I think he made a mistake.

128
00:09:29,861 --> 00:09:31,863
Got the wrong guy.

129
00:09:36,201 --> 00:09:38,203
OLIVER:
I could've shot you, killed you.

130
00:09:38,369 --> 00:09:40,747
-What the hell?
-Not gonna let you William Tell...

131
00:09:40,914 --> 00:09:43,083
-...an innocent man.
-Gaynor isn't innocent.

132
00:09:43,249 --> 00:09:45,418
You seem to think that
because of your book...

133
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:49,297
-...which you trust more than you trust me.
-I trust my father.

134
00:09:49,464 --> 00:09:53,760
And he explained to me that every name
on that list has a reason to be there.

135
00:09:53,927 --> 00:09:57,931
You took that book off your father's
dead body. How could he be so chatty?

136
00:09:59,724 --> 00:10:03,645
A few years ago, I found a message
he left me explaining the list.

137
00:10:03,812 --> 00:10:06,481
How was that possible?
You were on a deserted island.

138
00:10:06,648 --> 00:10:09,567
I didn't say that I found it on the island.

139
00:10:11,027 --> 00:10:14,322
Diggle, for the past four months,
I've lied to...

140
00:10:14,489 --> 00:10:18,118
...hurt and hid things
from all the people that I care about.

141
00:10:18,284 --> 00:10:23,164
Do you really think that I would do all this
if I wasn't sure?

142
00:10:29,087 --> 00:10:31,673
Oliver, listen,
Gaynor got me into Blackhawk.

143
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:33,842
And I'm gonna prove he's innocent.

144
00:10:35,510 --> 00:10:36,553
And if he's isn't?

145
00:10:36,719 --> 00:10:37,762
[GUN COCKS]

146
00:10:39,764 --> 00:10:41,724
You owe me that.

147
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:44,853
You owe me at least that.

148
00:10:52,861 --> 00:10:55,947
-Were you stationed by the perimeter?
OLIVER: Yes.

149
00:10:56,114 --> 00:11:00,118
-And your report?
OLIVER: Everything's good, sir. No trouble.

150
00:11:00,285 --> 00:11:04,122
-How long have you been stationed here?
OLIVER: Uh, just arrived, sir.

151
00:11:04,831 --> 00:11:06,666
Yes, you do seem rather green.

152
00:11:09,252 --> 00:11:14,174
I don't recall the submarine bringing
in a phalanx of new troops lately.

153
00:11:16,593 --> 00:11:18,386
OLIVER:
Submarine?

154
00:11:18,553 --> 00:11:21,347
I thought everybody came in
to the island on the plane.

155
00:11:23,474 --> 00:11:25,643
Indeed they do.

156
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:33,610
I think you've tried on
every dress in the city.

157
00:11:33,776 --> 00:11:34,819
Heh. Totally worth it.

158
00:11:34,986 --> 00:11:36,029
[CHUCKLES]

159
00:11:36,196 --> 00:11:37,322
My friends are gonna freak.

160
00:11:37,488 --> 00:11:40,200
Yes, well, if your father were still alive,
he'd freak too.

161
00:11:40,366 --> 00:11:42,452
Though in an entirely different way.

162
00:11:42,619 --> 00:11:45,788
Heh, like when he saw what I was
wearing to my first boy-girl dance?

163
00:11:45,955 --> 00:11:50,501
That poor boy you went with.
Oh, Robert scared him to death.

164
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:55,340
You know, Dad used to say his saddest
day would be when I turned 18.

165
00:11:56,841 --> 00:12:00,011
Now he's gone
and I'm the one that's sad.

166
00:12:02,721 --> 00:12:04,390
[PHONE RINGS]

167
00:12:04,557 --> 00:12:06,309
Ah, sorry.

168
00:12:08,561 --> 00:12:09,979
I need to take this.

169
00:12:11,981 --> 00:12:13,608
Hello?

170
00:12:14,651 --> 00:12:17,779
Yes, I understand
but I'm with my daughter.

171
00:12:20,657 --> 00:12:23,159
All right. I'll be there.

172
00:12:25,578 --> 00:12:26,621
[SIGHS]

173
00:12:26,788 --> 00:12:28,206
We were gonna
spend the whole day together.

174
00:12:28,373 --> 00:12:31,834
I know, but, uh...

175
00:12:32,001 --> 00:12:35,296
...compliance needs to file
the 8K connected...

176
00:12:35,463 --> 00:12:39,384
...to my assuming Walter's position
at the company and they can't wait.

177
00:12:41,177 --> 00:12:42,804
I'm sorry.

178
00:12:44,973 --> 00:12:49,602
-Is everything okay? You look worried.
-Not worried. Just...

179
00:12:52,689 --> 00:12:54,607
My father called.

180
00:12:55,316 --> 00:12:56,818
Oh.

181
00:12:57,819 --> 00:13:00,238
-And how did that go?
-He invited us to dinner.

182
00:13:00,405 --> 00:13:01,614
For tonight.

183
00:13:01,780 --> 00:13:02,824
Oh.

184
00:13:02,991 --> 00:13:05,410
Yeah. Apparently,
he wants to mend some fences.

185
00:13:05,576 --> 00:13:08,246
But thanks to him, I can't afford a fence.

186
00:13:08,413 --> 00:13:10,498
I assume he's got some other agenda.

187
00:13:10,665 --> 00:13:12,583
Well, there's only one way to find out.

188
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:16,337
And maybe he really is trying to extend
an olive branch.

189
00:13:18,715 --> 00:13:21,759
You really do look for the best in people,
don't you?

190
00:13:22,260 --> 00:13:23,928
Lucky for you.

191
00:13:24,095 --> 00:13:25,638
[CHUCKLES]

192
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:34,147
I'm sorry to have to pull you away
from your family.

193
00:13:34,314 --> 00:13:35,565
What do you want, Malcolm?

194
00:13:35,732 --> 00:13:38,067
We have a problem with your friend,
Carl Ballard.

195
00:13:38,985 --> 00:13:40,737
He's trying to gentrify the Glades.

196
00:13:42,864 --> 00:13:44,741
Carl knows that's not part of the plan.

197
00:13:44,907 --> 00:13:49,120
Which is why you're gonna shut him down.
You're his friend. He'll listen to you.

198
00:13:51,414 --> 00:13:55,376
You want me to help you with Carl,
I want something in return.

199
00:13:55,877 --> 00:13:58,588
Proof Walter's still alive.

200
00:14:00,757 --> 00:14:02,008
My word isn't enough?

201
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:03,259
[MOIRA SCOFFS]

202
00:14:03,426 --> 00:14:07,513
What's that saying? "Trust, but verify"?

203
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:13,019
Words to live by.

204
00:14:23,654 --> 00:14:26,532
GAYNOR: Two days later,
I'm still digging regurgitated tacos...

205
00:14:26,699 --> 00:14:30,244
...out of the car vents and he asks me
why I won't turn on the AC?

206
00:14:30,411 --> 00:14:31,454
[LAUGHING]

207
00:14:31,621 --> 00:14:34,290
All right, you win.
Bodyguarding Queen was never that bad.

208
00:14:34,457 --> 00:14:38,628
Six years serving, the only thing I'm
qualified for is babysitting spoiled brats.

209
00:14:38,795 --> 00:14:40,546
Ted, they're not all like that.

210
00:14:40,713 --> 00:14:43,549
I haven't met one yet
that would survive a single day in-country.

211
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:44,759
Hmm.

212
00:14:44,926 --> 00:14:46,844
Makes me wonder
what I was doing over there.

213
00:14:47,011 --> 00:14:48,179
CARLY:
Specialty of the house.

214
00:14:48,971 --> 00:14:50,890
-Thank you, Carly.
-Uh-uh, where is my cake?

215
00:14:51,057 --> 00:14:54,685
Tired of listening to you complain
about the cleaners shrinking your suits.

216
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:56,521
-Oh, yeah.
-Heh.

217
00:14:57,313 --> 00:14:58,356
[SCOFFS]

218
00:15:01,192 --> 00:15:04,195
-She likes you.
-She's my sister-in-law, Ted.

219
00:15:04,362 --> 00:15:08,616
Not anymore. Your brother's gone, John.

220
00:15:08,783 --> 00:15:11,202
But you are here.

221
00:15:13,996 --> 00:15:15,415
Car's waiting outside.

222
00:15:15,581 --> 00:15:18,251
We got a client to drop off
at the art gallery opening.

223
00:15:18,418 --> 00:15:19,794
GAYNOR:
You remember Paul Knox?

224
00:15:19,961 --> 00:15:22,964
He was a couple of ranks under us
back in the 'Stan.

225
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:27,510
Good to be working with you.

226
00:15:31,222 --> 00:15:33,099
I'll be outside.

227
00:15:36,727 --> 00:15:38,479
Didn't know Knox
worked at Blackhawk.

228
00:15:38,646 --> 00:15:41,482
They recruited him
when his tour ended last month.

229
00:15:41,649 --> 00:15:42,817
Mm-hm.

230
00:15:42,984 --> 00:15:45,528
People change, John.

231
00:15:45,695 --> 00:15:47,864
And everyone deserves
a chance to prove it.

232
00:15:59,542 --> 00:16:00,835
[TYPING ON KEYBOARD]

233
00:16:01,002 --> 00:16:02,587
[COMPUTER BEEPS]

234
00:16:04,922 --> 00:16:05,965
[DOOR OPENING]

235
00:16:06,132 --> 00:16:09,343
OLIVER: Knocking is not just a suggestion.
-I need to talk to you.

236
00:16:09,510 --> 00:16:12,972
Thea, I'm not telling you
if Mom's getting you a car.

237
00:16:13,139 --> 00:16:16,350
Heh, it's not about that.

238
00:16:16,517 --> 00:16:20,438
Remember last week when I asked you
if you thought Mom was acting weird?

239
00:16:20,605 --> 00:16:24,150
-Yep.
-Well, I found out why.

240
00:16:24,317 --> 00:16:26,527
She's hooking up with Tommy's dad.

241
00:16:26,694 --> 00:16:27,904
[SCOFFS]

242
00:16:28,070 --> 00:16:31,699
-That's insane.
-I just saw them together.

243
00:16:31,866 --> 00:16:35,328
-It's happening all over again.
-What are you talking about?

244
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:38,206
Um...

245
00:16:40,750 --> 00:16:46,130
A couple months
before you and Dad left on the <i>Gambit</i>...

246
00:16:46,297 --> 00:16:49,217
-...Mom and Dad were arguing a lot.
-About what?

247
00:16:49,383 --> 00:16:55,932
I don't know. But she was having a lot
of these lunch meetings with Mr. Merlyn.

248
00:16:56,098 --> 00:16:57,433
And now Walter's gone too...

249
00:16:57,600 --> 00:17:01,479
...and Mom and Mr. Merlyn
are back at it. It's gross.

250
00:17:02,355 --> 00:17:07,235
Mom never would've cheated on Dad.
She's not cheating on Walter.

251
00:17:07,401 --> 00:17:08,444
[SIGHS]

252
00:17:09,529 --> 00:17:14,700
You don't wanna believe because you have
this perfect image of Mom in your head.

253
00:17:14,867 --> 00:17:21,832
That's not who she is, Ollie.
She's a liar and a cheater.

254
00:17:22,792 --> 00:17:25,920
And you really don't know her at all.

255
00:17:38,516 --> 00:17:40,393
Malcolm and I, having an affair?

256
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:42,645
That it started when Dad was still alive.

257
00:17:42,812 --> 00:17:45,815
-Why would she think that?
-She says you and Dad were fighting.

258
00:17:45,982 --> 00:17:48,693
-Oh, dear God.
-Mom?

259
00:17:48,859 --> 00:17:52,863
-It's not your concern, sweetheart.
-Thea made it my concern.

260
00:17:56,492 --> 00:17:58,661
What was going on?

261
00:18:04,917 --> 00:18:11,215
Robert was unfaithful to me.
Repeatedly.

262
00:18:12,883 --> 00:18:16,804
It made our marriage difficult,
to say the least.

263
00:18:17,847 --> 00:18:21,309
I'm sorry. But your father wasn't always
the man you thought he was.

264
00:18:21,475 --> 00:18:22,518
[SCOFFS]

265
00:18:22,685 --> 00:18:24,186
I know you thought he walked on water.

266
00:18:24,353 --> 00:18:27,106
But you see, that's how I wanted you
to remember him...

267
00:18:27,273 --> 00:18:29,233
...as a good man who loved you.

268
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:34,905
That's how I want Thea to remember him.
So promise me you'll keep it a secret.

269
00:18:36,907 --> 00:18:38,492
Of course.

270
00:18:42,163 --> 00:18:44,582
-Mom?
-Yes?

271
00:18:44,749 --> 00:18:48,210
Why would Thea think you and Mr. Meryln
are still sneaking around?

272
00:18:49,378 --> 00:18:52,048
Well, I can't imagine.

273
00:18:54,050 --> 00:18:55,593
Have you seen him lately?

274
00:18:57,053 --> 00:18:58,763
Oliver.

275
00:18:58,929 --> 00:19:00,181
[CHUCKLES]

276
00:19:00,348 --> 00:19:03,643
He's been the CEO
of Merlyn Global Group for years.

277
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:07,355
I've been running
Queen Consolidated mere weeks.

278
00:19:07,521 --> 00:19:10,858
Yes, I occasionally go
and ask for advice.

279
00:19:14,570 --> 00:19:16,364
Is my interrogation over?

280
00:19:35,800 --> 00:19:37,426
FYERS:
See, this is where we, uh...

281
00:19:38,094 --> 00:19:43,224
...detain prisoners prone to running off
before I've finished with them.

282
00:19:43,391 --> 00:19:44,433
[OLIVER GRUNTS]

283
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:46,560
[THUDS]

284
00:19:47,978 --> 00:19:49,063
[OLIVER COUGHS]

285
00:19:53,401 --> 00:19:54,735
[PANTS]

286
00:19:54,902 --> 00:19:57,863
Prisoners like you, Mr. Queen.

287
00:20:03,494 --> 00:20:07,665
At Christmas one year,
Tommy wanted a puppy.

288
00:20:08,332 --> 00:20:11,293
He wanted to name it Arthur,
as in King Arthur...

289
00:20:12,002 --> 00:20:13,546
...because he's a Merlyn.

290
00:20:13,713 --> 00:20:16,590
Heh. Well, you used to be
so incredibly adorable.

291
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:18,259
-I still am.
-Heh.

292
00:20:18,426 --> 00:20:19,802
My wife would've liked you, Laurel.

293
00:20:22,096 --> 00:20:23,472
LAUREL:
I wish I would've known her.

294
00:20:23,639 --> 00:20:26,016
She passed away
before Tommy and I became friends.

295
00:20:26,183 --> 00:20:29,895
She was killed.
There's no need to be polite about it.

296
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:31,981
You are just a ray of sunshine today.

297
00:20:32,148 --> 00:20:35,025
Please forgive me.
Talking about my wife has a tendency...

298
00:20:35,192 --> 00:20:37,570
...to make me a little bit maudlin.

299
00:20:44,869 --> 00:20:47,413
And here I was beginning
to think my days of being...

300
00:20:47,580 --> 00:20:49,457
...Oliver's geek were coming to an end.

301
00:20:49,623 --> 00:20:54,211
-Is that your way of saying you missed me?
-No, but if that works for you, go with it.

302
00:20:54,378 --> 00:20:56,756
Heh. A friend is running
a scavenger hunt...

303
00:20:56,922 --> 00:21:00,009
...and there's a case
of Lafite Rothschild 1982...

304
00:21:00,176 --> 00:21:02,261
-...waiting at the end.
-Oh, I love red wine.

305
00:21:02,428 --> 00:21:05,931
But in order to find it,
I first need to get through this.

306
00:21:07,141 --> 00:21:08,225
Hmm.

307
00:21:08,392 --> 00:21:09,769
Security fob.

308
00:21:16,859 --> 00:21:17,902
[DEVICE BEEPS]

309
00:21:18,778 --> 00:21:20,029
[TYPING ON KEYBOARD]

310
00:21:20,196 --> 00:21:21,864
It's PIN protected.

311
00:21:22,031 --> 00:21:25,701
Response goes back to a company called
Blackhawk Squad Protection Group.

312
00:21:25,868 --> 00:21:28,120
My friend had his bodyguard
set it up for him.

313
00:21:28,287 --> 00:21:30,873
Personally, I think it's cheating,
but whatever.

314
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:34,710
This is a military-grade cryptographic
security protocol.

315
00:21:34,877 --> 00:21:39,256
-Your friend really went to all this trouble?
-The idle rich are hard to entertain.

316
00:21:40,299 --> 00:21:46,180
Listen, you get through it
and one of those bottles of wine is yours.

317
00:21:58,234 --> 00:22:01,195
This has been lovely, Mr. Merlyn.
Thank you.

318
00:22:01,362 --> 00:22:02,655
Thank you for joining me.

319
00:22:02,822 --> 00:22:05,533
It's been wonderful
getting to know you better.

320
00:22:06,158 --> 00:22:08,953
If Tommy doesn't mind me
mixing business with pleasure...

321
00:22:09,119 --> 00:22:11,580
...I could use your signature on these.

322
00:22:24,552 --> 00:22:26,428
You wanna shut down
Mom's free clinic?

323
00:22:26,595 --> 00:22:30,224
-It's not hers anymore, Tommy.
-That clinic meant everything to Mom.

324
00:22:30,391 --> 00:22:34,728
You were 8. I don't think you were in
a position to know what was important.

325
00:22:34,895 --> 00:22:37,106
-I just need your signature...
TOMMY: Stop.

326
00:22:37,648 --> 00:22:41,110
This dinner was never about
getting to know Laurel...

327
00:22:41,277 --> 00:22:42,570
...it was about this.

328
00:22:54,372 --> 00:22:56,584
You haven't changed
and you never will.

329
00:22:58,085 --> 00:23:02,298
It's about time that I learn that
and stop letting you disappoint me.

330
00:23:03,757 --> 00:23:05,634
We're leaving.

331
00:23:08,971 --> 00:23:12,474
-This clinic was his mother's.
MALCOLM: Yes.

332
00:23:12,641 --> 00:23:14,476
And his mother taught him a lesson...

333
00:23:14,643 --> 00:23:17,730
...that the world is a harsh
and unforgiving place.

334
00:23:17,897 --> 00:23:19,315
When did she teach him that?

335
00:23:23,277 --> 00:23:27,156
When she was lying dead in the street
with a bullet in her head.

336
00:23:29,867 --> 00:23:31,744
Good night.

337
00:23:36,206 --> 00:23:39,168
GAYNOR: Management keeps things
running smooth, which is nice.

338
00:23:39,335 --> 00:23:41,629
Better than going to war
with the army you got, right?

339
00:23:41,795 --> 00:23:45,215
Heh. Indeed. Indeed.

340
00:23:45,716 --> 00:23:48,761
So, Ted, are you the reason
Knox is working for Blackhawk?

341
00:23:48,928 --> 00:23:51,847
Look, I know you don't like the guy.

342
00:23:52,014 --> 00:23:54,516
I wasn't his biggest fan either.

343
00:23:54,683 --> 00:23:57,728
But jobs are hard to come by
for everybody these days.

344
00:23:57,895 --> 00:23:59,563
And guys like us?

345
00:23:59,730 --> 00:24:02,900
When all anyone thinks you're qualified for
is shooting at people?

346
00:24:03,067 --> 00:24:04,735
If I hadn't gotten Knox this job...

347
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:09,949
...chances are he'd be out knocking over
liquor stores or robbing banks.

348
00:24:13,994 --> 00:24:15,037
[PHONE RINGING]

349
00:24:16,872 --> 00:24:18,958
-What'd you get?
FELICITY: <i>Your friend's bodyguard...</i>

350
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,668
-...gave him the wrong fob.
-Why?

351
00:24:20,834 --> 00:24:23,671
Well, once I got past Blackhawk's
authentication system...

352
00:24:23,837 --> 00:24:26,882
...there wasn't anything
about a scavenger hunt.

353
00:24:27,049 --> 00:24:29,259
Just a directory and...

354
00:24:29,426 --> 00:24:32,596
Well, I think you've stumbled onto
or gotten me to stumble onto...

355
00:24:32,763 --> 00:24:35,099
-...something pretty illegal.
-Define illegal.

356
00:24:35,265 --> 00:24:39,770
Oh, you know, robbing an armored car
with grenade launchers and tear gas.

357
00:24:39,937 --> 00:24:41,730
-What?
-Someone at Blackhawk...

358
00:24:41,897 --> 00:24:44,149
...was using their system
to store schedules...

359
00:24:44,316 --> 00:24:46,819
...for the city's
seven major armored car carriers.

360
00:24:46,986 --> 00:24:51,615
Including the three that have been hit. We
should provide this information to police.

361
00:24:51,782 --> 00:24:53,951
They should be able
to predict the next heist.

362
00:24:54,118 --> 00:24:55,411
Hold on, Felicity.

363
00:24:55,577 --> 00:24:58,330
I don't wanna get you in trouble.
Do me a favor.

364
00:24:58,496 --> 00:25:02,251
Forward that directory on to me
and I'll get it to the police personally.

365
00:25:02,418 --> 00:25:04,211
Thank you.

366
00:25:06,171 --> 00:25:08,090
So no wine then?

367
00:25:33,741 --> 00:25:34,742
[MAN GRUNTS]

368
00:25:35,492 --> 00:25:36,910
[GUNFIRE]

369
00:25:55,262 --> 00:25:56,472
[GROANING]

370
00:25:56,638 --> 00:25:58,849
Blake? Blake? Come on, man, come on.

371
00:25:59,016 --> 00:26:00,267
[GRUNTS]

372
00:26:05,439 --> 00:26:06,482
[GRUNTS]

373
00:26:07,274 --> 00:26:11,820
-Blake is hit. He's hit!
-Come on, come on!

374
00:26:11,987 --> 00:26:13,781
Go. Drive, drive, drive.

375
00:26:13,947 --> 00:26:15,282
[TIRES SCREECH]

376
00:26:25,834 --> 00:26:27,461
[DANCE MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

377
00:26:29,379 --> 00:26:31,340
[CROWD CHEERING]

378
00:26:35,844 --> 00:26:37,638
Oh, God, check it out. Check it out.

379
00:26:37,805 --> 00:26:41,058
-Convertible. Oh, my God.
-You must be so surprised.

380
00:26:41,225 --> 00:26:45,854
Isn't everything absolutely perfect?
Except for if Dad were here.

381
00:26:46,647 --> 00:26:50,359
If Dad were here,
he'd say you look beautiful.

382
00:26:52,528 --> 00:26:54,488
-Oh, excuse me a sec.
OLIVER: Mm-hm.

383
00:27:01,078 --> 00:27:03,956
DIGGLE: I heard the Hood foiled
an armored car heist earlier.

384
00:27:04,123 --> 00:27:05,791
Gaynor wasn't running
the rocket launcher.

385
00:27:05,958 --> 00:27:07,793
I was with him the whole time.

386
00:27:08,794 --> 00:27:10,546
Looks like you were right.

387
00:27:10,712 --> 00:27:14,091
If someone at Blackhawk is involved,
I'd put my money on Knox.

388
00:27:14,258 --> 00:27:17,261
He started right before the heists began.
He has training.

389
00:27:17,427 --> 00:27:18,846
Okay, I injured one of them.

390
00:27:19,012 --> 00:27:21,765
He was bleeding badly
when they made off in their van.

391
00:27:21,932 --> 00:27:24,726
If any of Knox's blood is in one
of the motor pool vans...

392
00:27:24,893 --> 00:27:26,603
-...we'll know.
-I'm going with you.

393
00:27:26,770 --> 00:27:30,524
No, listen, you have this party
and I told you I would handle this.

394
00:27:30,691 --> 00:27:34,194
-Any problems, you're a phone call away.
-Hey.

395
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:36,947
Head on a swivel.

396
00:27:37,698 --> 00:27:40,033
That's the way I was born, man.

397
00:27:45,247 --> 00:27:47,665
-Happy birthday.
-Oh, thank you.

398
00:27:47,833 --> 00:27:50,794
We have a special birthday gift for you.
It's called Vertigo.

399
00:27:50,961 --> 00:27:53,046
Supposed to make you feel all floaty.

400
00:27:53,213 --> 00:27:56,717
Ah, heh, if my mom caught me with this,
I wouldn't make it to 19.

401
00:27:56,884 --> 00:27:59,761
I'm gonna go put it upstairs
and then I'll be right back down.

402
00:28:09,687 --> 00:28:12,149
Moira, I have a little something for you.

403
00:28:13,066 --> 00:28:14,401
MOIRA:
Walter.

404
00:28:15,903 --> 00:28:19,781
I did as you asked.
Now it's your turn to do as I asked.

405
00:28:19,948 --> 00:28:24,203
MOIRA: I'll take care of it.
-Thank you, Moira.

406
00:28:29,041 --> 00:28:33,795
-At my party. Right here in front of me?
-No, Thea, you don't understand.

407
00:28:33,962 --> 00:28:38,133
Walter hasn't been gone two months
and you're already cheating on him.

408
00:28:38,300 --> 00:28:40,886
-Just like you cheated on Dad...
-No, I never cheated...

409
00:28:41,053 --> 00:28:44,973
-Like I would believe anything you say.
-Thea. Thea.

410
00:28:45,140 --> 00:28:49,686
I wish it had been you
that was on that boat.

411
00:29:48,036 --> 00:29:49,621
[GUNS COCK]

412
00:29:49,788 --> 00:29:52,124
KNOX:
I had a feeling you'd show up.

413
00:29:53,208 --> 00:29:54,960
DIGGLE:
Yeah? Why is that, Knox?

414
00:29:55,127 --> 00:29:58,005
KNOX: Right after Gaynor got you hired,
someone hacked our system.

415
00:29:58,171 --> 00:30:00,090
First person to ever make it through.

416
00:30:00,257 --> 00:30:04,261
-You wanna tell me how you did it?
-Not really sure.

417
00:30:04,428 --> 00:30:06,847
-He didn't think you'd be very cooperative.
-Who?

418
00:30:13,312 --> 00:30:14,396
Hey, John.

419
00:30:19,151 --> 00:30:22,904
-Ted, you're part of this?
GAYNOR: No, not part of.

420
00:30:23,405 --> 00:30:26,742
My men. My mission.

421
00:30:26,908 --> 00:30:28,785
Mission?

422
00:30:28,952 --> 00:30:33,123
-This isn't Afghanistan.
-Oh, don't I know that.

423
00:30:33,290 --> 00:30:38,211
Over there, we were trusted with millions
of dollars in weapons and personnel.

424
00:30:38,378 --> 00:30:40,756
We were conquerors.

425
00:30:40,922 --> 00:30:43,842
And now? We're nannies with Tasers.

426
00:30:44,009 --> 00:30:45,052
[SCOFFS]

427
00:30:46,636 --> 00:30:50,223
So that gives you the right to steal?

428
00:30:50,390 --> 00:30:54,561
-To kill innocent civilians?
-I'm not gonna convince you I'm right.

429
00:30:54,728 --> 00:30:58,565
-I am gonna convince you to join the team.
-Heh. Yeah, now I know you're crazy.

430
00:30:59,399 --> 00:31:02,527
Tonight was supposed to be our last score.
Because of the Hood...

431
00:31:02,694 --> 00:31:04,571
...we struck out.

432
00:31:04,738 --> 00:31:10,369
Now we're down a man. Good thing
you're qualified to take his place.

433
00:31:10,535 --> 00:31:11,578
[SCOFFS]

434
00:31:11,745 --> 00:31:14,915
I think your convincing
is gonna have to be a lot more convincing.

435
00:31:17,292 --> 00:31:20,462
Copy that. Cavanaugh.

436
00:31:20,629 --> 00:31:21,671
[DOOR OPENS]

437
00:31:22,714 --> 00:31:23,757
[CARLY GRUNTING]

438
00:31:23,924 --> 00:31:26,134
DIGGLE:
Carly.

439
00:31:26,301 --> 00:31:27,677
You son of a bitch.

440
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:33,100
-No, don't. Don't. Wait. Don't.
-Knox.

441
00:31:33,683 --> 00:31:34,726
[MUFFLED SCREAMS]

442
00:31:38,105 --> 00:31:41,024
You both can die tonight, John.

443
00:31:41,191 --> 00:31:45,362
Or once we do this, we're on a plane
and she can go home to your nephew.

444
00:31:45,529 --> 00:31:47,489
[OVER COMM]
<i>It's your call.</i>

445
00:32:16,184 --> 00:32:17,227
[HORN HONKS]

446
00:32:23,233 --> 00:32:24,276
Oh.

447
00:32:25,694 --> 00:32:27,737
Come on, let's go. Ugh.

448
00:32:27,904 --> 00:32:30,198
KNOX:
Oh, you shouldn't have done that, Dig.

449
00:32:30,365 --> 00:32:32,451
Now you gotta watch us
kill your girlfriend.

450
00:32:32,617 --> 00:32:35,787
-No, please don't.
DIGGLE: You're forgetting one thing, guys.

451
00:32:35,954 --> 00:32:37,497
Oh, yeah? What's that?

452
00:32:37,664 --> 00:32:40,208
I'm the one with the grenade launcher.

453
00:32:42,085 --> 00:32:43,837
Carly, get out of there.

454
00:32:44,004 --> 00:32:45,005
[GRUNTS]

455
00:32:53,847 --> 00:32:54,890
[PANTS]

456
00:33:25,170 --> 00:33:27,214
DIGGLE: Freeze!
-Oh.

457
00:33:29,633 --> 00:33:30,675
[GASPS]

458
00:33:30,842 --> 00:33:32,427
DIGGLE:
Drop it, Ted.

459
00:33:32,594 --> 00:33:34,095
Or I swear...

460
00:33:34,262 --> 00:33:37,474
Don't posture.

461
00:33:38,808 --> 00:33:41,144
You're not gonna do it.

462
00:33:42,187 --> 00:33:45,524
You can't. I can see it in your eyes.

463
00:34:03,458 --> 00:34:07,212
-You're late.
-You knew I was coming?

464
00:34:11,007 --> 00:34:14,844
DIGGLE: Next time you plant a bug
on someone, be more subtle about it.

465
00:34:16,179 --> 00:34:19,808
-I wish you'd trusted me though.
-I trusted you.

466
00:34:21,142 --> 00:34:24,980
But them, never.

467
00:34:26,606 --> 00:34:27,607
[POLICE SIREN WAILING]

468
00:34:29,234 --> 00:34:31,319
You should get out of here.

469
00:34:36,366 --> 00:34:38,243
John.

470
00:34:46,042 --> 00:34:48,378
Carly, are you okay?

471
00:34:49,212 --> 00:34:51,756
OFFICER: Turn around
and put your hands where I can see them.

472
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:55,468
[CLUB MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

473
00:35:03,435 --> 00:35:04,477
[TIRES SCREECH]

474
00:35:06,271 --> 00:35:07,314
[GLASS SHATTERS]

475
00:35:20,577 --> 00:35:23,580
[WOMAN SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY OVER PA]

476
00:35:28,668 --> 00:35:30,587
Oh, Thea.

477
00:35:30,754 --> 00:35:33,923
-Are you okay?
-Yeah, yeah, I'm fine.

478
00:35:34,090 --> 00:35:36,217
Just headachey, really.

479
00:35:37,052 --> 00:35:41,014
-The car, is it...?
-The car isn't important right now.

480
00:35:41,181 --> 00:35:42,932
[SIGHS]

481
00:35:43,099 --> 00:35:44,809
Do you remember what happened,
sweetheart?

482
00:35:44,976 --> 00:35:46,019
[SCOFFS]

483
00:35:47,062 --> 00:35:49,439
Just go away.

484
00:35:50,815 --> 00:35:55,904
-Thea, please.
-I said, I'm fine.

485
00:36:05,205 --> 00:36:06,247
[PHONE RINGING]

486
00:36:06,790 --> 00:36:08,375
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON TELEVISION]

487
00:36:10,001 --> 00:36:12,170
Your father's even beginning
to call me now.

488
00:36:12,337 --> 00:36:14,297
Don't waste your minutes.

489
00:36:14,923 --> 00:36:15,965
[SIGHS]

490
00:36:17,008 --> 00:36:20,637
Your father's a jerk,
but he's still your father.

491
00:36:27,060 --> 00:36:30,480
I think, in his own way...

492
00:36:30,647 --> 00:36:33,817
I think he sees himself
as protecting you somehow.

493
00:36:33,983 --> 00:36:36,903
Yeah, he is really good
at using my dead mother...

494
00:36:37,070 --> 00:36:39,072
...for an excuse for being a jerk.

495
00:36:39,989 --> 00:36:41,741
You never talk about your mother.

496
00:36:43,868 --> 00:36:47,539
I was only 8. I don't remember much
about what happened.

497
00:36:49,374 --> 00:36:51,334
But after?

498
00:36:51,918 --> 00:36:55,547
My father completely shut me out.

499
00:37:01,761 --> 00:37:03,722
And then he went away.

500
00:37:05,432 --> 00:37:09,894
He was gone for a year, maybe two.

501
00:37:10,061 --> 00:37:16,735
<i>I was 8 and he left me.
That is who my father is.</i>

502
00:37:18,611 --> 00:37:21,156
<i>He only cares about himself.</i>

503
00:37:38,882 --> 00:37:40,759
-Cops give you a hard time?
DIGGLE: No.

504
00:37:40,925 --> 00:37:44,804
I explained them that me and Gaynor were
old war buddies. He tried to rope me in...

505
00:37:44,971 --> 00:37:47,140
[SIGHS]

506
00:37:47,307 --> 00:37:50,351
When I refused, he kidnapped Carly,
everything else happened under duress.

507
00:37:50,518 --> 00:37:51,561
[OLIVER SIGHS]

508
00:37:57,066 --> 00:37:59,194
I screwed up, Oliver.

509
00:38:01,237 --> 00:38:04,574
Obviously Gaynor wasn't
who I thought he was.

510
00:38:05,909 --> 00:38:07,952
I was wrong.

511
00:38:08,119 --> 00:38:12,916
Yeah, but you were right too.

512
00:38:15,877 --> 00:38:19,964
When you told me that I trusted the list
more than I trusted you.

513
00:38:21,007 --> 00:38:24,928
Diggle, the truth is,
after what happened to me on the island...

514
00:38:28,348 --> 00:38:33,436
...it's difficult for me to trust anything.

515
00:38:35,897 --> 00:38:37,065
But you do.

516
00:38:39,526 --> 00:38:42,570
And that reminded me
why I chose you as my partner.

517
00:38:44,113 --> 00:38:46,950
It's because you see the best in people.

518
00:39:21,818 --> 00:39:23,069
I learned something too.

519
00:39:25,154 --> 00:39:29,242
Until you tell me, I don't ever wanna know
what other names are in this book.

520
00:39:39,419 --> 00:39:41,462
OLIVER:
She promised she's not cheating on Walter.

521
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:44,173
THEA: Like I would trust
anything that woman says.

522
00:39:44,340 --> 00:39:46,301
OFFICER:
Miss Queen? Thea Queen?

523
00:39:46,467 --> 00:39:49,095
-There a problem?
-We received a call from your doctor.

524
00:39:49,262 --> 00:39:53,308
In the event of a vehicular accident,
they report the results of the tox-screen.

525
00:39:53,474 --> 00:39:57,228
Ms. Queen tested positive
for a narcotic called Vertigo.

526
00:39:57,395 --> 00:39:58,438
[SIGHS]

527
00:39:58,605 --> 00:39:59,814
The drug they're using in the Glades?

528
00:39:59,981 --> 00:40:03,943
OFFICER: Thea Queen, you are under arrest
for driving under the influence of narcotics.

529
00:40:12,285 --> 00:40:15,663
Do you know why my men
wear balaclavas, Mr. Queen?

530
00:40:17,540 --> 00:40:20,501
Because it masks everything
but the eyes.

531
00:40:20,668 --> 00:40:24,714
And in a man's eyes,
one can always find the truth.

532
00:40:25,965 --> 00:40:29,344
You risked everything
to save your friend.

533
00:40:29,510 --> 00:40:31,971
Someone I warned you about...

534
00:40:32,138 --> 00:40:34,599
...and yet you trusted him.

535
00:40:34,766 --> 00:40:37,685
But that trust was misplaced.

